Just now

--

In the first part of this series I said that every idle game is resource extraction, and that under the theme it all reduces to a new amount equals a base plus its bonuses. This part is about the three systems that turn that bare equation into something you can sit and play: resources, production, and prestige. These are the load-bearing walls of Pure Idle, my space incremental game built solo in JavaScript on an HTML5 Canvas. When I later describe cutting whole systems out of the game, none of these three moved. They are the parts I never had to apologize for.
Let me take them in the order the player meets them.
You can read the first part of this article here.
Author: Aleksei Makarenko. Pen names: Alex Vuorenmaa, Riven Elow.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Akif Waseem on Unsplash
Resources: the things you gather
Pure Idle has twelve resources, and they split into two groups. Seven are primary — the ones the player watches climb in the corner of the screen. Five are intermediate — made inside the production chains, spent to make something higher up. In code the whole economy is just this list of numbers starting at zero:
class PureResources {
constructor() {
// Primary - what the player collects and prestiges on:
this.stardust = 0;
this.energy = 0;
this.mass = 0;
this.essence = 0;
this.darkEnergy = 0;
this.cosmicShards = 0;
this.cosmicEssence = 0;
// Intermediate - forged inside production chains:
this.plasma = 0;
this.alloy = 0;
this.crystal = 0;
this.quantumDust = 0;
this.cosmicAlloy = 0;
}
}The split matters for design, not just tidiness. Primary resources are the ones the player has feelings about — stardust is the first thing you ever earn, dark energy is your reward for a reset. Intermediate resources are plumbing: plasma and alloy exist only so that a chain has a middle, a step between “collect stardust” and “make something that needed three earlier things.” Without a middle, a production chain is not a chain; it is a single conversion. The intermediate resources are what let the factory have depth.
I will be honest about one thing here, because this series is meant to be honest: not every one of these twelve is doing heavy lifting in the final balance. Some earn their place; a couple mostly sit in the plumbing. Keeping the field in the code costs nothing and keeps saves stable, so they stayed. But if I were counting only the resources a player actively chases, the real number is smaller than twelve.
Production: the one system with real interlock
If resources are the nouns, production is the only place in Pure Idle where the verbs genuinely interlock. It is a grid where the player places buildings and links them into chains. Each building is a small, declared object — its shape, its color, what it eats, what it makes, what it costs, and which technology unlocks it:
const BUILDING_TYPES = {
star_collector: {
name: 'Star Collector', tier: 1,
input: null, output: 'stardust', baseOutput: 1.5,
baseCost: { stardust: 100 },
requiredTech: 'production_conveyor',
},
energy_siphon: {
name: 'Energy Siphon', tier: 3,
inputMode: 'percent', input: 'stardust', inputPercent: 0.015,
output: 'energy', outputRatio: 0.2, baseOutput: 1,
baseCost: { stardust: 60 },
requiredTech: 'production_energy_siphon_tech',
},
essence_crucible: {
name: 'Essence Crucible', tier: 4,
inputMode: 'percent', input: ['energy', 'mass'], inputPercents: [0.02, 0.02],
output: 'essence', outputRatio: 0.25, baseOutput: 1,
baseCost: { stardust: 400, plasma: 2 },
requiredTech: 'production_essence_tech',
},
// …
};Read those three and the chain draws itself. A Star Collector pulls raw stardust out of nothing. An Energy Siphon and a Mass Forge each eat stardust and turn it into energy and mass. An Essence Crucible eats both energy and mass and produces essence. Higher still, a Dark Condenser turns essence into dark energy. Each tier depends on the one below it, so the factory is a small pyramid: broad, cheap producers at the bottom, rare and demanding ones at the top.
The percentage model, and why I chose it
The interesting design decision is how a building consumes and produces. I did not use flat rates (“this building eats 5 stardust per second”). Flat rates break the moment your numbers get large — an idle game’s numbers always get large — because 5 per second is everything early on and a rounding error an hour later. So production runs on percentages of the current stock:
// A building takes this share of each input's current stock per tick:
const PROD_INPUT_PERCENT = 0.10; // 10% of what you have
// …and outputs this share of the smallest input it received:
const PROD_OUTPUT_PERCENT = 0.005; // 0.5%
// Prestige resources are deliberately stingier:
const PROD_OUTPUT_PERCENT_PRESTIGE = 0.001;A percentage scales with the player forever. Ten percent of your stardust is meaningful whether you have a hundred or a quintillion. This one choice is why the factory never becomes trivial and never becomes impossible — it breathes with the player instead of being outrun by them. The output being tied to the smallest input is the other half of the trick: a chain is only as strong as its weakest feeder, so the player is always nudged to go fix the starved link rather than pile onto the fat one.
Two special buildings bend these rules on purpose. A Storage Tank is a boost. Link it to a building and that building’s appetite drops — it eats eight percent of its input stock per tick instead of ten — while its output stays exactly the same. Less spent for the same made is, in plain terms, an efficiency bonus:
// A connected Storage Tank lowers the consumer's input draw: 10% → 8%.
const PROD_INPUT_PERCENT = 0.10;
const PROD_TANK_INPUT_REDUCTION = 0.02;
// …at run time:
const tankReduction = this._tankInputReductionFor(originKey) || 0;
const inputPct = Math.max(0, PROD_INPUT_PERCENT - tankReduction); // 0.08 when a tank is attachedAn Amplifier is the other kind of helper — a catalyst. It makes nothing itself; it just multiplies a connected building’s output.
amplifier: {
name: 'Amplifier', tier: 5,
input: null, output: null, baseOutput: 0,
modifier: 'amplify', modifierValue: 1.5, // boosts a connected building ×1.5
requiredTech: 'production_amplifier_tech',
},Boosts and catalysts are what turn “place buildings” into “design a layout.” They are the reason two players with the same buildings can have factories of different strength.
Making a chain “spin” in one tick
There is a subtle problem hiding in any production chain. If a Star Collector makes stardust, and an Energy Siphon eats stardust, and a Crucible eats the Siphon’s energy — in what order do they run? If they run in the wrong order once per tick, the stardust made this frame does not reach the Siphon until next frame, and the whole chain crawls one step per tick.
My fix is to run the tick in multiple passes. Each building runs at most once per tick, and the loop keeps sweeping the grid until a full pass makes no further progress:
tick(game) {
// Reset the "already ran" flag on every building.
for (const ok of origins) {
const b = this.grid[ok];
if (b) b._ranThisTick = false;
}
// Sweep the grid up to 24 times; stop early when nothing new fires.
for (let pass = 0; pass < PRODUCTION_TICK_MAX_PASSES; pass++) {
let progressed = false;
for (const originKey of origins) {
const building = this.grid[originKey];
if (!building || building._ranThisTick) continue;
if (this._tickTryRunBuilding(game, originKey, building, /* … */)) {
building._ranThisTick = true;
progressed = true;
}
}
if (!progressed) break; // whole chain has settled
}
}This is a small, humble version of an idea real engines use for dependency graphs: keep resolving until nothing changes. The cap of twenty-four passes is a safety rail so a strange layout can never lock the game in an endless loop. The `if (!progressed) break;` is the part I am quietly proud of — it means simple factories cost almost nothing (they settle in one pass), and only deep chains pay for their depth.
Prestige: throwing it all away, on purpose
Prestige is the mechanic that makes an idle game idle rather than a single climb that ends. You reset your progress in exchange for a permanent boost, and start again faster. Pure Idle has two layers of this.
The smaller reset is Collapse. You give up your current run and receive dark energy in proportion to what you had. The formula is deliberately plain — sum the primary resources, take one percent, floor it:
getCollapseDarkEnergyFromResources(resources) {
let sum = 0;
for (const k of this.COLLAPSE_DE_SUM_KEYS) {
const v = Math.max(0, Number(resources.get(k)) || 0);
sum += v * 0.01;
}
return Math.max(0, Math.floor(sum));
}I want to point at one thing next to this function, because it is a habit that runs through the whole codebase. Right below it sits an older reward formula — a square-root curve I used in an earlier version — marked `@deprecated` and left in place:
/** @ deprecated kept so old saves that still call it don't break. */
getCollapseDarkEnergy(totalSD, collapseCount) {
return Math.floor(Math.sqrt(totalSD / 80) * (1.35 + 0.13 * collapseCount));
}I almost never delete working code. I comment it out or mark it deprecated and leave it where it was. On a project maintained by one non-programmer, over many months, the thing that kills you is not messy code — it is silently changing behavior a save somewhere still depends on. Dead code that is clearly labeled is cheap insurance. You will see the same discipline again in Part 3, where an entire disabled building still sits in the file with a comment explaining that it is unreachable but preserved.
The larger reset is Ascension. It costs dark energy — rising each time, `ceil(50 × 1.08^ascensions)` — and pays out cosmic shards, the top-tier currency. Shards buy permanent upgrades in a Cosmic Workshop: a little more income, a little more speed, a little more of the dark-energy yield itself. Each layer of prestige feeds the one below it, so the loop has a shape: collapse many times inside one run, ascend occasionally to bank shards, spend shards to make every future run faster.
Prestige also reaches into production, and this is where the systems stop being separate. An ordinary Ascension wipes your factory back to the ground — unless you have bought the Cosmic Factory upgrade, in which case your higher-tier buildings survive the reset. In code that “what survives” rule is a single tier threshold:
// Ascension without the Cosmic Factory upgrade: keep nothing above the living tiers.
const PRODUCTION_KEPT_MIN_TIER_ASCENSION = 6;
// Ascension WITH Cosmic Factory: keep tier ≥ 3 (the real machines);
// only the cheap tier-1 starters reset, and they re-place instantly.
const PRODUCTION_KEPT_MIN_TIER_FACTORY_ASCEND = 3;That one number is a whole design conversation compressed into a constant. It answers “how much of my hard work do I lose when I ascend?” and it turns the Cosmic Factory upgrade from a stat bonus into an emotional one: it is the thing that lets you keep the factory you loved.
Why these three survived everything
Resources, production, prestige. A list of numbers, a grid that transforms them, and a ritual of throwing it away for a permanent edge. That is the entire spine of Pure Idle, and it is a spine the genre has used for years — because it works, and because there is no prize for reinventing it. Everything I built around this core was an attempt to make it feel richer. Some of those attempts earned their keep. Some, as the next parts will show, only looked like depth.
The next part is about the largest of those attempts: a technology tree that once held over five hundred nodes, why so many of them were the same idea wearing different names, and what happened when I cut it down.
